tors of the violence thatdestabilized the kingdom. The author argues that chivalry was far from being a code of good behaviour, scrupulously observed, but rather encouraged knights to avenge themselves violently upon their neighbours, pursue a zealous holy war against Islam, and tear at the social fabric of Castilian society. Their powerful ideas and values shaped the course of Castilian history in the crucial years before the unification of the Spanish kingdoms. SAMUEL A. CLAUSSEN is Assistant Professor of History at California Lutheran University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChivalryxHistoryzSpainzCastile. 0aKnights and knighthoodxHistoryzSpainzCastile. 4aHispanic Studies. 4aMedieval History. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Military / Biological & Chemical Warfare.2bisacsh  aCatholic Monarchs.  aFerdinand and Isabella.  aGolden Age.  aGranada.  aReconquista.  aTrastamara.  acrusade.  aholy war.  aknights.  apeasant revolt.  asocial violence.  awar.  awarfare.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787448469?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787448469423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787448469/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles